properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:

properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: An intense low pressure system will bring significant amounts of rain beginning Monday evening through Tuesday evening over Southern and Central Quebec. Further north, snowfall amounts of 15 to 25 centimetres are possible from Monday morning to Tuesday evening in a corridor stretching from Abitibi towards Chaleur Bay, including Quebec City. Snow accompanied by moderate winds may reduce visibilities locally in blowing snow. Freezing rain is likely in the vicinity of the snow-to-rain transition area. A more important episode of freezing rain is also likely for areas of the St. Lawrence Valley between Montreal and Quebec City. Travel could be difficult, especially at rush hour Tuesday morning. There is still much uncertainty about the track of this system and thus about the type and amount of precipitation expected. Please stay tuned for future forecasts. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.

properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Freezing rain is expected or occurring. A cold front moving through southern Saskatchewan this evening is causing freezing rain along it's leading edge. The precipitation may begin as rain in above zero temperatures but quickly changes over to freezing rain as the front moves through and the temperatures drop. The precipitation should turn to snow later this evening and end Sunday by morning. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Freezing rain warnings are issued when rain falling in sub-zero temperatures creates ice build-up and icy surfaces. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: An upper disturbance moving through central Manitoba today will bring an additional swath of snow at times heavy. General amounts across central Manitoba will see 5 to 10 cm today with another 2 to 4 cm tonight for storm totals around 15 to 25 cm. The largest snowfall area is expected to be in a narrow band between The Pas and Swan River, east through the Lake Manitoba north basin. To the south, the accompanying cold front will move through southern portions of the province this morning bringing flurries with a risk of freezing rain and freezing drizzle. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A period of very cold wind chills continues. Bitterly cold air remains in place over Kivalliq this morning as a ridge of high pressure sits to their south. The cold temperatures combined with moderate to strong winds from the accompanying low pressure system to their east have created extreme wind chill values in the -55 to -60 range. These wind chill values are expected to moderate later this morning. The strong winds caused by these two systems continue to create blowing snow conditions with near zero visibilities for Chesterfield Inlet this morning. As the low pushes further east this afternoon, the winds will moderate and the blizzard will end. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Risks are greater for young children, older adults, people with chronic illnesses, people working or exercising outdoors, and those without proper shelter. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A prolonged period of very cold wind chills continues. Strong northwest winds of 40 gusting 60 km/h combined with bitterly cold air is bringing near-blizzard conditions with wind chill values between -55 and -60 to Hall Beach and Igloolik this morning. The near-blizzard conditions and extreme wind chill values are expected to continue through today before moderating Monday morning. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Risks are greater for young children, older adults, people with chronic illnesses, people working or exercising outdoors, and those without proper shelter. Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Blowing Snow Advisory In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Poor visibility in snow and blowing snow is expected or occurring in some locations. Total snowfall: further snowfall near 5 cm. Maximum wind gusts: increasing to northerly 70 km/h. Time span: until later morning or early this afternoon Remarks: Fresh will combine with strong northerly winds to produce reduced visibility in blowing snow. Conditions are forecast to improve later this morning or early this afternoon as the snow tapers off and the winds ease. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility in some locations. Blowing snow advisories are issued when winds are expected to create blowing snow giving poor visibility to 800 metres or less for at least 3 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NLstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NLwx.
